The collected bacterial samples were incubated at 35 ± 0.5 °C temperature for 24–48 h (Heo et al. 2014) while fungal samples at 20–28 °C for 3–7 days (Hoseini et al. 2013), respectively. The bioaerosol concentration was expressed as colony forming units per cubic meter of air (CFU/m3) after the standard positive-hole correction method was taken into account to statistically correct the counting (Ponce-Caballero et al. 2013). The formula used for calculating bioaerosol concentration is as follows:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \mathrm{Bioaerosolconcentration}\left(\mathrm{CFU}/\mathrm{m}3\right)=\mathrm{No}.\mathrm{ofcolonies}/\left(\mathrm{flowrate}\left(\mathrm{m}3/\min \right)\times \mathrm{time}\left(\min \right)\right) $$\end{document}Bioaerosolconcentration(CFU/m3)=No.ofcolonies/(flowrate(m3/min)×time(min))
